---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Getting Started">

  <section class="gs-intro">
    <p class="gs-eyebrow">Setup Guide</p>
    <h1 class="gs-h1">Getting started</h1>
    <p class="gs-summary">
      The UX Intelligence agents run inside <strong>Claude Code</strong> — available as a desktop
      app that connects Claude directly to a local copy of this repository on your machine.
      There are four things to set up: GitHub access and cloning the repo, the Git command-line
      tool, the Claude Code desktop app with its connectors, and the agent skills. This guide
      walks you through each in order.
    </p>
    <div class="gs-notice">
      <strong>Why Claude Code, not Claude.ai?</strong>
      Claude.ai can chat and analyse pages, but it can't write files to this repository or push
      commits — so reports won't be saved and screenshots won't appear on the site. Claude Code
      runs in the context of the repo on your machine, which is what gives it permission to
      create report files, commit screenshots, and push everything live.
    </div>
    <p class="gs-terminal-note">
      <strong>Prefer the terminal?</strong> If you're already comfortable with git and npm,
      <code>npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code</code> then <code>claude</code> from
      inside the repo is all you need. The rest of this guide focuses on the desktop app.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PART 1 — GITHUB
  ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="gs-part">
    <div class="gs-part-header">
      <span class="gs-part-badge">Part 1</span>
      <h2 class="gs-part-title">GitHub</h2>
      <p class="gs-part-desc">Create an account, get repo access, install GitHub Desktop, and clone the repo to your machine.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Account -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">1</span>
        Create a GitHub account
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        If you don't already have one, sign up for a free GitHub account. You'll need this to
        request access to the private repository.
      </p>
      <a href="https://github.com/signup" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link">
        <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
        github.com/signup — create a free account
      </a>
      <p class="gs-body gs-body--note">
        Use your THG work email address so it's easy for the repo admin to verify who you are
        when granting access.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Repo access -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">2</span>
        Request access to the repository
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        The repository is private. Once you have a GitHub account, contact Richard Gill and
        share your GitHub username — he'll add you as a collaborator and GitHub will send you
        an email invite. Accept the invite to gain write access.
      </p>
      <div class="gs-repo-card">
        <div class="gs-repo-header">
          <span class="gs-repo-icon">◈</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-repo-org">THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds</p>
            <p class="gs-repo-name">ux-prototyping</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="gs-repo-desc">
          The UX Intelligence site and all agent-generated reports. Private — requires an invite.
        </p>
        <a href="https://github.com/THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds/ux-prototyping" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-repo-link">
          View on GitHub →
        </a>
      </div>
      <p class="gs-body gs-body--note">
        Write access is required — not just read access. This is what allows Claude Code to commit
        new report files and push them to the site on your behalf.
      </p>
      <div class="gs-tip">
        <strong>Authorise for SSO</strong>
        The <code>THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds</code> organisation uses single sign-on. After accepting
        the invite, go to <a href="https://github.com/settings/organizations" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-inline-link">github.com/settings/organizations</a>
        and click <strong>Authorize</strong> next to <code>THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds</code>. If you skip
        this, GitHub Desktop will look like it's working but pushes will silently fail with a
        permissions error.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- GitHub Desktop + clone -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">3</span>
        Install GitHub Desktop and clone the repo
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        The agents write report files directly into the local repo folder on your machine.
        <strong>GitHub Desktop</strong> is the easiest way to clone the repo and push changes
        back to GitHub — it handles authentication so you don't need to set up SSH keys or
        use the terminal.
      </p>

      <div class="gs-substeps">

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">3a</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Download GitHub Desktop</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">Install GitHub Desktop and sign in with your GitHub account.</p>
            <a href="https://desktop.github.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link">
              <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
              desktop.github.com
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">3b</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Clone the repository</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              In GitHub Desktop: <strong>File → Clone Repository</strong>, then search for
              <code>THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds/ux-prototyping</code>. Choose a local path you'll
              remember — for example <code>~/Documents/GitHub/ux-prototyping</code>. Click
              <strong>Clone</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">3c</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Note the local path</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              In GitHub Desktop, go to <strong>Repository → Show in Finder</strong> (Mac) or
              <strong>Show in Explorer</strong> (Windows). Note the full folder path — you'll
              need to point Claude Code at this folder in Part 3.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PART 2 — GIT
  ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="gs-part">
    <div class="gs-part-header">
      <span class="gs-part-badge">Part 2</span>
      <h2 class="gs-part-title">Git</h2>
      <p class="gs-part-desc">Install the Git command-line tool that Claude Code needs to commit and push files.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">4</span>
        Install Git
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Claude Code needs the <code>git</code> command-line tool to commit changes and push
        reports to the site. <strong>GitHub Desktop doesn't include it</strong> — you need to
        install it separately.
      </p>

      <div class="gs-substeps">

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">Mac</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Install via Xcode Command Line Tools</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Open the <strong>Terminal</strong> app (search Spotlight for "Terminal") and paste
              this command, then press Enter:
            </p>
            <div class="gs-copyblock">
              <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="git-install-mac">xcode-select --install</pre>
              <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
                navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('git-install-mac').innerText);
                this.textContent = 'Copied!';
                setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
              ">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              A dialog will appear asking to install the Command Line Tools — minimise any open
              windows so you can see it, then click <strong>Install</strong>. It takes 5–10 minutes.
              Once done, run <code>git --version</code> in Terminal to confirm.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">Win</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Download Git for Windows</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Download and run the installer from the official Git site. Accept all the defaults.
            </p>
            <a href="https://git-scm.com/download/win" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link">
              <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
              git-scm.com/download/win
            </a>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Once installed, open <strong>Command Prompt</strong> or <strong>PowerShell</strong>
              and run <code>git --version</code> to confirm it worked.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PART 3 — CLAUDE DESKTOP
  ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="gs-part">
    <div class="gs-part-header">
      <span class="gs-part-badge">Part 3</span>
      <h2 class="gs-part-title">Claude Desktop</h2>
      <p class="gs-part-desc">Install the Claude Code desktop app, open the repo as a project, and connect the Chrome and GitHub plugins.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Install app -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">5</span>
        Install the Claude Code desktop app
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Claude Code is built into the Claude desktop app. Download it from Anthropic and sign in
        with your Anthropic account. A Claude Pro plan ($20/month) is sufficient for running the agents.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-body gs-body--note">
        <strong>Who pays for this?</strong> Check with your team lead before signing up — THG may
        already have Claude seats or an expense process for this.
      </p>
      <a href="https://claude.ai/download" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link">
        <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
        claude.ai/download — download the desktop app
      </a>
      <div class="gs-tip">
        <strong>Already use Claude.ai?</strong>
        Use the same credentials to log in to the desktop app — it's the same account.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Open repo -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">6</span>
        Open the repository in Claude Code
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        This connects Claude Code to the local repo folder — without this, the agents can't
        write report files or commit screenshots.
      </p>

      <div class="gs-substeps">

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">6a</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Switch to Claude Code</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Open the Claude desktop app. In the top-left, click the <strong>Claude</strong>
              menu (or the dropdown next to your workspace name) and select
              <strong>Claude Code</strong>. It's still just a chat window — but with access to
              files on your machine.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">6b</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Select the repo folder</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Claude Code will prompt you to select a project folder. Navigate to the
              <code>ux-prototyping</code> folder you cloned in step 3 and select it. Claude
              Code now has access to all the repo files and can write new ones.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">6c</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Confirm it's working</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Type <code>/</code> in the prompt. You should see a list of available slash commands.
              If the list appears, the session is running correctly inside the repo.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Connectors -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">7</span>
        Connect the Chrome and GitHub plugins
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Two plugins are needed: a Chrome browser extension so Claude can navigate to pages and
        take screenshots, and a GitHub connector for deeper repo integration.
      </p>

      <div class="gs-plugin-card">
        <div class="gs-plugin-header">
          <span class="gs-plugin-badge gs-plugin-badge--chrome">Chrome</span>
          <h3 class="gs-plugin-name">Claude in Chrome extension</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="gs-plugin-desc">
          Connects Claude Code to your Chrome browser. Without it, the UX Review and Competitor
          Analysis agents can't open URLs, scroll pages, or take screenshots.
        </p>
        <div class="gs-plugin-steps">
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">1</span> Install the extension from the Chrome Web Store:</p>
          <a href="https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/claude/pnaoflhkifljdmpmollaobhbknaeeafh" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link gs-external-link--sm">
            <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
            Claude extension — Chrome Web Store
          </a>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">2</span> Once installed, click the extension icon in Chrome and sign in with the same account you use in the desktop app.</p>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">3</span> In Claude Code, type <code>/</code> and look for Chrome-related tools in the list to confirm it's connected.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="gs-plugin-card">
        <div class="gs-plugin-header">
          <span class="gs-plugin-badge gs-plugin-badge--github">GitHub</span>
          <h3 class="gs-plugin-name">GitHub MCP connector</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="gs-plugin-desc">
          Gives Claude Code deeper GitHub integration — it can read repository structure, check
          commit history, and authenticate pushes more reliably.
        </p>
        <div class="gs-plugin-steps">
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">1</span> In the Claude desktop app, click the <strong>+</strong> button at the bottom of the chat box and select <strong>Plugins</strong>.</p>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">2</span> Find <strong>GitHub</strong> in the plugin list and click <strong>+</strong> to add it.</p>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">3</span> If prompted, authorise Claude to access your GitHub account and approve access for the <code>THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds</code> organisation.</p>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">4</span> Once added, it persists across sessions — you only need to do this once.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="gs-body gs-body--note" style="margin-top: 12px; margin-bottom: 0;">
          If GitHub doesn't appear in the plugin list, it may not be available on your Claude plan.
          Basic git operations still work without it — GitHub Desktop handles authentication for pushes.
        </p>
      </div>

    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PART 4 — AGENT SKILLS
  ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="gs-part">
    <div class="gs-part-header">
      <span class="gs-part-badge">Part 4</span>
      <h2 class="gs-part-title">Agent skills</h2>
      <p class="gs-part-desc">Register each agent skill using the built-in skill creator. This takes about 2 minutes per skill and only needs to be done once.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">8</span>
        Install each skill using /skill-creator
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        The UX Intelligence agents are packaged as <em>skills</em> — named workflows that Claude
        runs when you type a slash command. Skills must be registered through Claude's built-in
        <code>/skill-creator</code> tool. This writes each skill into Claude's local manifest so
        it persists across sessions and app restarts.
      </p>
      <div class="gs-callout gs-callout--info">
        <strong>Install one at a time.</strong> Type <code>/skill-creator</code> in Claude Code,
        paste the prompt for that skill, and wait for it to finish before moving to the next.
        Do this with the <code>ux-prototyping</code> repo open as your project folder.
      </div>

      <div class="gs-skill-install-list" style="margin-top: 20px;">

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/myprotein-ux-review</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">UX Review agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-1">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/myprotein-ux-review/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-1').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/competitor-analysis</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">Competitor Analysis agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-2">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/competitor-analysis/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-2').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/design-qa</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">Design QA agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-3">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/design-qa/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-3').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/myprotein-prep-agent</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">Project Prep agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-4">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/myprotein-prep-agent/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-4').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/figma-engineering-handover</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">Engineering Handover agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-5">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/figma-engineering-handover/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-5').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">9</span>
        Verify all five skills are registered
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Type <code>/</code> in Claude Code to open the slash command picker. You should see all
        five agent commands in the list:
      </p>
      <div class="gs-skill-list">
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/myprotein-ux-review</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">UX Review agent</span>
        </div>
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/competitor-analysis</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">Competitor Analysis agent</span>
        </div>
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/design-qa</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">Design QA agent</span>
        </div>
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/myprotein-prep-agent</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">Project Prep agent</span>
        </div>
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/figma-engineering-handover</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">Engineering Handover agent</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="gs-body" style="margin-top: 12px;">
        If a skill is missing, re-run <code>/skill-creator</code> for that skill only.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── First run ────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="gs-section">
    <h2 class="gs-section-heading">
      <span class="gs-step-badge">9</span>
      Run your first report
    </h2>
    <p class="gs-body">
      You're ready. Trigger the UX Review agent with any Myprotein URL:
    </p>
    <pre class="gs-code">/myprotein-ux-review https://www.myprotein.com/sports-nutrition/impact-whey-protein/10530943.html</pre>
    <p class="gs-body">
      Claude Code will navigate to the page in Chrome, take screenshots, analyse the UX, write
      the report file, and commit and push it to GitHub — all automatically. Once it's pushed,
      you'll need to trigger a deploy in the <strong>Altitude dashboard</strong> to make it
      live on the site. The agent will remind you of this when it finishes.
    </p>
    <div class="gs-tip">
      <strong>What is Altitude?</strong>
      Altitude is THG's internal hosting platform — it's where this site is deployed from.
      Pushing to GitHub doesn't automatically publish your changes; someone with Altitude
      access needs to log in and trigger a manual deploy. If you don't have access, ask
      Richard Gill to either set you up with an account or deploy on your behalf after you push.
    </div>

    <p class="gs-body" style="margin-top: 8px;">
      See the <a href="/agents/ux-review" class="gs-inline-link">agent guides</a> for a
      detailed walkthrough of each agent, what to expect at every step, and how to handle
      common issues.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Troubleshooting ────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="gs-section">
    <h2 class="gs-section-heading">Common setup issues</h2>
    <ul class="gs-tips-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Claude Code can't find the repo folder.</strong>
        Make sure you selected the root <code>ux-prototyping</code> folder — not a subfolder
        like <code>src/</code> or <code>src/pages/</code>. The repo root is the folder that
        contains <code>package.json</code> and <code>src/</code>. If you're not sure, use
        GitHub Desktop's <strong>Show in Finder / Explorer</strong> to open the exact folder,
        then drag that folder into Claude Code's project selector.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Slash commands show up but the agents don't run — just errors.</strong>
        The most common cause is the Chrome extension not being connected. Open Chrome, click
        the Claude extension icon, and make sure it shows as connected (not "disconnected" or
        "sign in required"). The UX Review and Competitor Analysis agents both need Chrome open
        and connected before they'll work.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>GitHub Desktop push fails — "permission denied" or "authentication failed".</strong>
        This usually means you accepted the repo invite but GitHub Desktop hasn't refreshed your
        permissions. In GitHub Desktop, go to <strong>GitHub Desktop → Preferences → Accounts</strong>,
        sign out, and sign back in. Then try the push again.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>A skill isn't appearing after running /skill-creator.</strong>
